#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.Unbuffered:3
msgid "This is implemented by forcing a flush after each write."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.ignore_signal:1
msgid "Context manager to temporarily ignore a signal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:1
msgid "Context manager to disable line editing and echoing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:3
msgid "Use this with ``sys.stdin`` for keyboard input, e.g.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:5
msgid ""
"with keyboard_input(sys.stdin) as kb:\n"
"    while True:\n"
"        kb.check_fg_bg()\n"
"        r, w, x = select.select([sys.stdin], [], [])\n"
"        # ... do something with keypresses ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:11
msgid ""
"The ``keyboard_input`` context manager disables canonical (line-based) input "
"and echoing, so that keypresses are available on the stream immediately, and "
"they are not printed to the terminal. Typically, standard input is line-"
"buffered, which means keypresses won't be sent until the user hits return. "
"In this mode, a user can hit, e.g., 'v', and it will be read on the other "
"end of the pipe immediately but not printed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:19
msgid ""
"The handler takes care to ensure that terminal changes only take effect when "
"the calling process is in the foreground. If the process is backgrounded, "
"canonical mode and echo are re-enabled. They are disabled again when the "
"calling process comes back to the foreground."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:24
msgid ""
"This context manager works through a single signal handler for ``SIGTSTP``, "
"along with a poolling routine called ``check_fg_bg()``. Here are the "
"relevant states, transitions, and POSIX signals::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:28
msgid ""
"[Running] -------- Ctrl-Z sends SIGTSTP ------------.\n"
"[ in FG ] <------- fg sends SIGCONT --------------. |\n"
"   ^                                              | |\n"
"   | fg (no signal)                               | |\n"
"   |                                              | v\n"
"[Running] <------- bg sends SIGCONT ---------- [Stopped]\n"
"[ in BG ]                                      [ in BG ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:36
msgid ""
"We handle all transitions exept for ``SIGTSTP`` generated by Ctrl-Z by "
"periodically calling ``check_fg_bg()``.  This routine notices if we are in "
"the background with canonical mode or echo disabled, or if we are in the "
"foreground without canonical disabled and echo enabled, and it fixes the "
"terminal settings in response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:42
msgid ""
"``check_fg_bg()`` works *except* for when the process is stopped with "
"``SIGTSTP``.  We cannot rely on a periodic timer in this case, as it may not "
"rrun before the process stops.  We therefore restore terminal settings in "
"the ``SIGTSTP`` handler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:47
msgid "Additional notes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:49
msgid ""
"We mostly use polling here instead of a SIGARLM timer or a thread. This is "
"to avoid the complexities of many interrupts, which seem to make system "
"calls (like I/O) unreliable in older Python versions (2.6 and 2.7).  See "
"these issues for details:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:54
msgid "https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0475/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:55
msgid "https://bugs.python.org/issue8354"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:57
msgid ""
"There are essentially too many ways for asynchronous signals to go wrong if "
"we also have to support older Python versions, so we opt not to use them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:61
msgid ""
"``SIGSTOP`` can stop a process (in the foreground or background), but it "
"can't be caught. Because of this, we can't fix any terminal settings on "
"``SIGSTOP``, and the terminal will be left with ``ICANON`` and ``ECHO`` "
"disabled until it is resumes execution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:66
msgid ""
"Technically, a process *could* be sent ``SIGTSTP`` while running in the "
"foreground, without the shell backgrounding that process. This doesn't "
"happen in practice, and we assume that ``SIGTSTP`` always means that "
"defaults should be restored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.keyboard_input:71
msgid ""
"We rely on ``termios`` support.  Without it, or if the stream isn't a TTY, "
"``keyboard_input`` has no effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:1
msgid "Context manager that logs its output to a file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:3
msgid "In the simplest case, the usage looks like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:5
msgid ""
"with log_output('logfile.txt'):\n"
"    # do things ... output will be logged"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:8
msgid ""
"Any output from the with block will be redirected to ``logfile.txt``. If you "
"also want the output to be echoed to ``stdout``, use the ``echo`` parameter::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:12
msgid ""
"with log_output('logfile.txt', echo=True):\n"
"    # do things ... output will be logged and printed out"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:15
msgid ""
"The following is available on Unix only. No-op on Windows. And, if you just "
"want to echo *some* stuff from the parent, use ``force_echo``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:19
msgid ""
"with log_output('logfile.txt', echo=False) as logger:\n"
"    # do things ... output will be logged\n"
"\n"
"    with logger.force_echo():\n"
"        # things here will be echoed *and* logged"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:25
msgid "See individual log classes for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.log_output:28
msgid ""
"This method is actually a factory serving a per platform (unix vs windows) "
"log_output class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.nixlog:1
msgid ""
"Under the hood, we spawn a daemon and set up a pipe between this process and "
"the daemon.  The daemon writes our output to both the file and to stdout (if "
"echoing).  The parent process can communicate with the daemon to tell it "
"when and when not to echo; this is what force_echo does.  You can also "
"enable/disable echoing by typing 'v'."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.nixlog:7
msgid ""
"We try to use OS-level file descriptors to do the redirection, but if stdout "
"or stderr has been set to some Python-level file object, we use Python-level "
"redirection instead.  This allows the redirection to work within test "
"frameworks like nose and pytest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.nixlog.force_echo:1 llnl.util.tty.log.winlog.force_echo:1
msgid "Context manager to force local echo, even if echo is off."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.replace_environment:1
msgid "Replace the current environment (`os.environ`) with `env`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.replace_environment:3
msgid ""
"If `env` is empty (or None), this unsets all current environment variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.winlog:1
msgid ""
"Similar to nixlog, with underlying functionality ported to support Windows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/llnl/util/tty/log.py:docstring of
#: llnl.util.tty.log.winlog:4
msgid "Does not support the use of 'v' toggling as nixlog does."
msgstr ""

